re, England":"Shelton, Bedfordshire, England","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Beeston, Norfolk, , England":"Beeston, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1547–1622":"1547–1622","1538–Male":"1538–Overleden","1540–1607":"1540–1607","1541–1581":"1541–1581","1556–Female":"1556–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1580–Female":"1580–Overleden","1515–1592":"1515–1592","1517–1607":"1517–1607","1592":"1592","1581":"1581","1580":"1580","24 Sep 1592":"24 september 1592","1547":"1547","1622":"1622","1556":"1556","1541":"1541","4 May 1607":"4 mei 1607","1540":"1540","1607":"1607","1517":"1517","1538":"1538","1515":"1515","Beeston, Norfolk, England":"Beeston, Norfolk, England","Shelton, Bedfordshire, England":"Shelton, Bedfordshire, England","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Beeston, Norfolk, , England":"Beeston, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1547–1622":"1547–1622","1538–Male":"1538–Deceased","1540–1607":"1540–1607","1541–1581":"1541–1581","1556–Female":"1556–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1580–Female":"1580–Deceased","1515–1592":"1515–1592","1517–1607":"1517–1607","1592":"1592","1581":"1581","1580":"1580","24 Sep 1592":"24 September 1592","1547":"1547","1622":"1622","1556":"1556","1541":"1541","4 May 1607":"4 May 1607","1540":"1540","1607":"1607","1517":"1517","1538":"1538","1515":"1515","Beeston, Norfolk, England":"Beeston, Norfolk, England","Shelton, Bedfordshire, England":"Shelton, Bedfordshire, England","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Beeston, Norfolk, , England":"Beeston, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hare","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hÍr</b> or <i>Ó hÉir</i> ‘descendant of <i>Ír</i>’, a personal name, possibly meaning ‘long-lasting’, borne by a legendary ancestor of the north of Ireland. This name was always monosyllabic.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hAichir</b> ‘descendant of <i>Aichear</i>’, a personal name derived from the epithet <i>aichear</i> ‘fierce, sharp’. The personal name on which this surname is based was originally disyllabic. Although the Anglicized forms <b>O'Hehir</b> and   Hehir   still exist, particularly in Ireland, pronunciation in later northern Irish has caused <i>Ó hAichir</i> to fall together with another surname, based on a one-syllable personal name, as in sense 1 above.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>hare</i>, <i>harr</i>, <i>here</i> ‘hare’ (Old English <i>hara</i>, sometimes influenced by Old Norse <i>heri</i>). It may have denoted someone who could run fast or was timorous, or who bore some similarity to a hare in appearance, such as bulging eyes."],"variants":[{"name":"Hehir","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brighid.","Irish (Clare): variant of   Hare   2 from <b>Ó hAichir</b>."]},{"name":"Hairr","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Hare   or   Hair  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German   Herr  ."]},{"name":"Haire","meanings":["Irish (northern): variant of   Hare   or   O'Hare  .","English: variant of   Hair  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Hare was born in 1547, in Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Hare, was 32 and his mother, Alice Sophia Rugge, was 30. He had at least 1 daughter with Nelle Harry. He died in 1622, in his hometown, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1547–1622":"1547–1622","1538–Male":"1538–Surnud","1540–1607":"1540–1607","1541–1581":"1541–1581","1556–Female":"1556–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1580–Female":"1580–Surnud","1515–1592":"1515–1592","1517–1607":"1517–1607","1592":"1592","1581":"1581","1580":"1580","24 Sep 1592":"24. september 1592","1547":"1547","1622":"1622","1556":"1556","1541":"1541","4 May 1607":"4. mai 1607","1540":"1540","1607":"1607","1517":"1517","1538":"1538","1515":"1515","Beeston, Norfolk, England":"Beeston, Norfolk, England","Shelton, Bedfordshire, England":"Shelton, Bedfordshire, England","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Beeston, Norfolk, , England":"Beeston, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1547–1622":"1547–1622","1538–Male":"1538–Kuollut","1540–1607":"1540–1607","1541–1581":"1541–1581","1556–Female":"1556–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1580–Female":"1580–Kuollut","1515–1592":"1515–1592","1517–1607":"1517–1607","1592":"1592","1581":"1581","1580":"1580","24 Sep 1592":"24. syyskuuta 1592","1547":"1547","1622":"1622","1556":"1556","1541":"1541","4 May 1607":"4. toukokuuta 1607","1540":"1540","1607":"1607","1517":"1517","1538":"1538","1515":"1515","Beeston, Norfolk, England":"Beeston, Norfolk, England","Shelton, Bedfordshire, England":"Shelton, Bedfordshire, England","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfor